    },
    {
      "id": "0dd3ecaa672585371c1c9f30f32e63a63eefa854",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-12-23 17:30:54.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nLiang, the difficulty with putting the CPT number at the top of the sequence is that it now makes it difficult in userspace to order the RPCs correctly. The reason the CPT number was in the low bits was that this allows the RPCs to be printed in roughly time order.\n\nProbably printing the RPCs in time order is more complex than needed, especially if the order is not critical for all users, but it should be possible to sort them in some manner.\n\nOne way to do this is to switch the CPT number into the low bits again only _when printing_ so that the seq pos works properly internally, but it is still possible to sort the entries by sequence in userspace if needed.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "2922ee8ee8f87e223627c941329c674779d2c710",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 176,
        "name": "Liang Zhen",
        "email": "liang.zhen@intel.com",
        "username": "liangzhen",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-12-25 14:07:22.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nAndreas, probably my patch comment is not clear enough, :-), this patch is exactly same as you suggested, I only switch bits while it's returned as read offset, and it will be switched back while search the position, that's all, I didn't change bits order of ptlrpc history sequence.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
